            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> I think you have to use `export GMT_DATADIR=/data` to define an environment variable.\r\n\r\nYou're absolutely right @seisman. Strange, I didn't think `export` was needed; doesn't gmt pick it up from the current shell?\r\n\r\nAlso funny,\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ GMT_DATADIR=/var\r\n$ gmt --show-datadir\r\nNot set\r\nexport GMT_DATADIR=/var\r\ngmt --show-datadir\r\n/var\r\n$ GMT_DATADIR=/var/log\r\n$ gmt --show-datadir\r\n/var/log\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo setting `GMT_DATADIR` without export does nothing (\"Not set\"). Do it again, with `export` and it's been \"initialized\" - now you don't need to put `export` in front of it if you want to change the path.\r\n\r\nAlso, does anyone know where this environment variable is stored?\r\nI thought it would be in the list created by `env`, but no;\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ GMT_DATADIR=/\r\n$ env | grep -i gmt\r\nPATH=/home/anbj/gems/bin:/home/anbj/gmt/build/bin:/home/anbj/.local/bin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/local/games:/usr/games:/home/anbj/.local/bin\r\n```",
